\f0\b \cf0 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 \
In the initial days of the COVID-19 pandemic in India and attempts at containment measures, life seemed to have taken unpredictable paths for individuals requiring healthcare services. A neighbour in Maharashtra had fractured his left thigh bone, a relative in Karnataka had a fall and needed to see an orthopedician, a chronic diabetic and hypertensive cancer survivor was worried about continuing supply and access to his medications. Both trauma cases with comorbidities had to visit multiple places in pain and without much respite, to be ultimately sent home as health facilities were gearing up to cater to COVID-19, while the elderly cancer survivor was able to stock up his medications with the help of his son. The thought for this article arose as some of us discussed issues being faced by our contacts in accessing healthcare and the fear settling in amongst them about various health circumstances which might require care in such times. \
\
Pandemics are not new to humankind, there has been extensive documentation and learning from these experiences. Invariably our health systems take most of the brunt as it caters to existing workload and simultaneously attempts to cope with the sudden demand. In the wake of COVID-19, the global community is grappling with ways to contain the virus as new developments are unfolding rapidly. India experimented with a one-day curfew on 22\super nd\nosupersub  March 2020 following which on 24\super th\nosupersub  March, a 21-day complete nationwide lockdown was announced. The health and police departments in coordination with the state and central administration are steering the implementation of the lockdown. On April 14\super th\nosupersub  2020 the lockdown was extended till May 3\super rd\nosupersub  2020 with conditional relaxation in areas where the spread has been contained from April 20\super th\nosupersub \
\
As per estimates from the 2009 influenza pandemic: school closures, quarantine and social distancing are the most expensive interventions in terms of costs per death prevented, whereas surveillance, contact tracing and face masks were the least expensive interventions.(1) India attempted to operationalize several of these measures for controlling COVID-19 but how does an overburdened healthcare system cope with this additional urgent need? COVID-19 seems to have overtaken the functioning of health facilities and the lockdowns have added additional challenges to seek routine care. In our attempt to highlight the moral and ethical challenges in accessing care, we share the externalities of COVID-19 on healthcare systems in India, immediate effects of the lockdown, and possible ways of addressing COVID and non-COVID related healthcare needs.\
\
The question we are trying to understand is \'91What is the effect of COVID-19 on the access to health care systems in India? (for emergency care, conditions requiring face to face contact and recurrent follow ups). Searches were conducted in the first week of April 2020 using a variety of sources such as academic literature, media reports, social media and websites. These searches pointed us to several healthcare difficulties that people are facing  during times of this pandemic and the subsequent lockdown.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 What has been the response of the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (MoHFW) as well as the major healthcare facilities to tackle non-COVID related healthcare needs?
\f1\b0 \
\
The Government at the national, state, district, and sub-district level swung into action activating existing systems, developing new systems, absorbing the rapidly changing guidelines, tapping on networks and resources. Figure 1 depicts a summary of the detailed guidelines for delivery of essential health services during COVID19 provided by the MoHFW on 14\super th\nosupersub  April 2020.(2) \
