\f1\b0 \cf0 \
In India, the COVID-19 pandemic has thrown open challenges at multiple fronts: (a) the reconfiguration of care in hospitals and other healthcare providers, in response to COVID-19, has led to many patients having to delay their treatment who are suffering non-COVID conditions, and (b) the lockdown which though necessary has, however, affected people unequally, some being more worse-off than others. This article unpacks the externalities of COVID-19 on healthcare systems in India by raising  moral and ethical questions about the plight of patients with other medical conditions while accessing care. This article also proposes a set of actions in which healthcare systems can address COVID and non-COVID related healthcare needs.\
